To listen for the BOOT_COMPLETED action in Android and automatically start an app, you need to use a BroadcastReceiver. Specifically, you would create a BroadcastReceiver that listens for the `BOOT_COMPLETED` intent and then start your app as needed. Here's a simple example:

```java
public class BootCompletedReceiver extends BroadcastReceiver {
    @Override
    public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {
        if (Intent.ACTION_BOOT_COMPLETED.equals(intent.getAction())) {
            Intent startActivityIntent = new Intent(context, MainActivity.class); // Replace MainActivity with your starting activity
            startActivityIntent.addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);
            context.startActivity(startActivityIntent);
        }
    }
}
```

You also need to declare this receiver in your AndroidManifest.xml file with the appropriate permissions and intent filter:

```xml
<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.RECEIVE_BOOT_COMPLETED" />

<application ... >
    <receiver android:name=".BootCompletedReceiver">
        <intent-filter>
            <action android:name="android.intent.action.BOOT_COMPLETED" />
        </intent-filter>
    </receiver>
    <activity android:name=".MainActivity">
        <!-- Define your main activity's properties -->
    </activity>
</application>
```

This setup ensures that your app starts automatically after the device has booted.

