In Java, the type of object that can be caught and handled in the catch clause is Throwable or any of its subclasses, such as Exception, RuntimeException, or specific custom exceptions. The catch block is used to handle exceptions that may occur during the execution of a try block. The syntax of the catch block is as follows:

```java
try {
    // Code that might cause an exception
} catch (Throwable exceptionName) {
    // Code to handle the exception
}
```

The exceptionName is the variable that holds the Throwable object, and exceptionName can be any subclass of Throwable. When an exception is thrown from the try block, the catch block will catch it if the exception is a subclass of the specified class. If the exception is not a subclass of the specified class, or if no catch block is provided, the program will terminate and an error message will be displayed.

For example, in the given code snippet:

```java
try {
    //=-- Start:exsn1
    int numerator = 10;
    int denominator = 0;
    int result = numerator / denominator;
    //=-- End:exsn1
} catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
    ex.printStackTrace();
}
```

The catch block catches an ArithmeticException that may be thrown when the division by zero occurs in the try block. In the catch block, the exception is passed to the variable ex, and the `printStackTrace()` method is called to print the stack trace of the exception.

