In Java, you can use the `PipedOutputStream` and `PipedInputStream` classes to redirect standard error output to a file. The `PipedOutputStream` class is used to create a stream that can send data to a `PipedInputStream`. Here's an example of how you can redirect the standard error to a file named "error.log":

```java
import java.io.*;

public class ErrorRedirector {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Create a new file to store the error output
            FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("error.log");
            // Create a new piped output stream for sending data to the piped input stream
            PipedOutputStream pos = new PipedOutputStream();
            // Create a new piped input stream and connect it to the piped output stream
            PipedInputStream pis = new PipedInputStream(pos);

            // Create a new thread to write data to the piped output stream (simulating standard error output)
            Thread errorThread = new Thread(() -> {
                try {
                    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                        System.err.println("Error " + i);
                        pos.write("Error " + i + "\n".getBytes());
                        Thread.sleep(200);
                    }
                    pos.close();
                } catch (IOException | InterruptedException e) {
                    e.printStackTrace();
                }
            });

            // Redirect the standard error output to the piped output stream
            System.setErr(new PrintStream(pis));

            // Start the thread to simulate generating error output
            errorThread.start();

            // Read the output from the piped input stream and write it to the file
            int c;
            while ((c = pis.read()) != -1) {
                fos.write(c);
            }
            fos.close();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, a `PipedOutputStream` named `pos` is created and connected to a `PipedInputStream` named `pis`. The `System.setErr()` method is used to redirect the standard error output (represented by `System.err`) to the `PrintStream` created from the `PipedInputStream`. When an error occurs, it is both printed to the console and written to the file "error.log" using the `FileOutputStream`. This allows you to capture and log error messages separately from the standard output.

