To handle binary data such as file downloads in XMLHttpRequest, the `responseType` property should be set to `"blob"`. This returns the data as a `Blob` object, which is suitable for dealing with raw binary data like files.

Here's an example of how to set the `responseType` to `"blob"` and handle a file download:

```javascript
// Create a new XMLHttpRequest object
var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

// Define the function to run when the request is complete
xhr.onload = function() {
  if (this.status === 200) {
    // Create a Blob object from the response data
    var blob = new Blob([this.response], { type: 'application/octet-stream' });

    // Create a URL for the Blob object
    var url = window.URL.createObjectURL(blob);

    // Create an anchor element to trigger the download
    var a = document.createElement('a');
    a.href = url;
    a.download = 'downloaded_file.zip';

    // Append the anchor to the document body and click it
    document.body.appendChild(a);
    a.click();

    // Clean up: revoke the object URL and remove the anchor
    window.URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
    document.body.removeChild(a);
  }
};

// Set the request type and URL
xhr.open('GET', 'http://example.com/downloaded_file.zip');

// Optional: set the request header if needed
xhr.setRequestHeader('Content-Type', 'application/xml');

// Set the responseType to 'blob' to handle binary data
xhr.responseType = 'blob';

// Send the request
xhr.send();
```

In this example, the `responseType` is set to `'blob'`, which allows the XMLHttpRequest to correctly interpret the server response as binary data. Once the response is received, it is converted into a `Blob` object, and a URL is created for this blob. An anchor element is then used to trigger the download of the file, and the URL is revoked and the anchor removed after the download is initiated.

